3D Editor is the first step of a three-step workflow. Basic 3D editing features are provided here.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="3D Editor"><br><br>

## Move/Translate

3D items can be moved around by entering values into `X`, `Y`, and `Z` input fields.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Move/Translate"><br><br>

## Scale

3D items can be scaled **uniformly** by using input fields. The `X`, `Y` and `Z` inputs are intentionally locked together to ensure a uniform scale.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Scale"><br><br>

## Rotate

3D items can be rotated by input fields.

* `X`, `Y` and `Z` are orthogonal components of a vector around which the 3D item would rotate
* Angle is the rotation angle around the (`X`, `Y`, `Z`) vector

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Rotate"><br><br>

## Drag handles

There are drag handles in *red*, *green*, and *blue* colors for these operations:

* Move/translation
* Scale
* Rotation

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Move/translate drag handle"><br><br>

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Scale drag handle"><br><br>

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Rotation drag handle"><br><br>

### Distance to Floor

It's possible to set the distance from lowest point to print floor for all 3D items. Any newly imported 3D item would satisfy this requirement too.
 
<img src="data:image/png;base64,"  alt="Distance to floor"><br><br>

## Auto Orientation

3D items can be oriented automatically to have the least amount of overhang areas to minimize the required support structure.

<img src="data:image/png;base64,"  alt="Auto Orientation"><br><br>

## Packing

Auto packing works in `XY` plane by setting a space between bounding boxes and arranging the 3D items on the print floor.

<img width=100% src="data:image/png;base64,"  alt="Packing"><br><br>

## Hollowing

3D items can be hollowed by the following parameters. If the parameters are *not* selected properly, the 3D item might *not* be actually hollowed. For example if the *wall thickness* is too large.

<img src="data:image/png;base64,"  alt="Hollowing"><br><br>

### Hollowing Parameters

#### Wall Thickness

Hollowing result wall thickness.

#### Consistency

Lower consistency means wall thickness would be less accurate, but the hollowing process would be faster. With a low accuracy, the result wall thickness might be uneven.

#### Min Cavity Size

Cavities smaller than this fill distance are going to be filled by hollowing process. Accordingly, sharp corners are going to be filled too.

## Tag

3D items can be tagged by a text with custom font and size.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Tagging"><br><br>

## Repair

3D items can be repaired. More info is made available by [a post](https://www.nanodlp.com/2021/11/08/stl-mesh-repair/). The repair process tries to:

* Harmonize normal vectors.
* Remove non-manifolds.
* Fix indices.
* Fix degenerations.
* Fix self-intersections.

There is just one parameter: *max number of edges*. It means the holes with the *max number of polygon edges* would be filled out. 

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Repair"><br><br>
